The span of such a labeling is the difference between the largest and smallest integers used. The math6 -number of math7 , denoted by math8 , is the minimum span over all math9 -labelings of math10 . Bodlaender et al. conjectured that if math11 is an outerplanar graph of maximum degree math12 , then math13 . Calamoneri and Petreschi proved that this conjecture is true when math14 but false when math15 . Meanwhile, they proved that math16 for any outerplanar graph G with math17 and asked whether or not this bound is sharp. In this paper we answer this question by proving that math18 for every outerplanar graph with maximum degree math19 . We also show that this bound math20 can be achieved by infinitely many outerplanar graphs with math21 .

source.text: html{border: 0px #006699 solid;border-left-width: 15px} body {margin: 15px;padding: 0px;background-color:#ffffff;color:black; font-family:helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 1.4em} div.volume-title {font-size:24pt;text-align:center;font-weight:bold} div.title {font-style:italic;font-weight:bold} div.mathics {font-size:larger;font-weight:bold} span.mathics-zbl {float:right} div.matverw {font-size:smaller} div.review {margin:5mm 5mm 5mm 5mm} div.aunot {font-weight:bold} div.published {font-weight:bold} .number {font-style: italic; text-align:right} div.reviewer{font-style:italic;text-align:right} EN 11G05 11G18 elliptic curve; torsion; Dihedral quartic number field; modular curve serial article Jeon, Daeyeol; Kim, Chang Heon; Lee, Yoonjin Number: 6110184 Infinite families of elliptic curves over Dihedral quartic number fields. 2013 Summary: We find infinite families of elliptic curves over quartic number fields with torsion group math1 with math2 . We prove that for each elliptic curve math3 in the constructed families, the Galois group math4 is isomorphic to the Dihedral group math5 of order 8 for the Galois closure math6 of math7 over math8 , where math9 is the defining field of math10 and math11 is a point of math12 of order math13 . We also notice that the plane model for the modular curve math14 found in Jeon et al. (2011) [1] is in the optimal form, which was the missing case in Sutherland’s work (Sutherland, 2012 [12]).

We obtain bounds that are uniform in both math4 and the form itself. We also improve a bound on a sum of the form math5 , where the math6 are the Fourier coefficients of a holomorphic cusp form, math7 and math8 are any real numbers, and math9 . This last bound is uniform in math10 , but not with respect to the form.

source.text: html{border: 0px #006699 solid;border-left-width: 15px} body {margin: 15px;padding: 0px;background-color:#ffffff;color:black; font-family:helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 1.4em} div.volume-title {font-size:24pt;text-align:center;font-weight:bold} div.title {font-style:italic;font-weight:bold} div.mathics {font-size:larger;font-weight:bold} span.mathics-zbl {float:right} div.matverw {font-size:smaller} div.review {margin:5mm 5mm 5mm 5mm} div.aunot {font-weight:bold} div.published {font-weight:bold} .number {font-style: italic; text-align:right} div.reviewer{font-style:italic;text-align:right} EN 05C70 05C15 serial article Karabáš, Ján; Máčajová, Edita; Nedela, Roman Number: 6106899 6-decomposition of snarks. 2013 Summary: A snark is a cubic graph with no proper 3-edge-colouring. In 1996, Nedela and Škoviera proved the following theorem: Let math1 be a snark with an math2 -edge-cut, math3 , whose removal leaves two 3-edge-colourable components math4 and math5 . Then both math6 and math7 can be completed to two snarks math8 and math9 of order not exceeding that of math10 by adding at most math11 vertices, where the number math12 only depends on math13 . The known values of the function math14 are math15 (Goldberg, 1981) [6], and math16 (Cameron et al. 1987) [4]. The value math17 is not known and is apparently difficult to calculate. In 1979, Jaeger conjectured that there are no 7-cyclically-connected snarks. If this conjecture holds true, then math18 is the last important value to determine. The paper is aimed attacking the problem of determining math19 by investigating the structure and colour properties of potential complements in 6-decompositions of snarks. We find a set of 14 complements that suffice to perform 6-decompositions of snarks with at most 30 vertices. We show that if this set is not complete to perform 6-decompositions of all snarks, then math20 and there are strong restrictions on the structure of (possibly) missing complements. Part of the proofs are computer assisted.

source.text: html{border: 0px #006699 solid;border-left-width: 15px} body {margin: 15px;padding: 0px;background-color:#ffffff;color:black; font-family:helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 1.4em} div.volume-title {font-size:24pt;text-align:center;font-weight:bold} div.title {font-style:italic;font-weight:bold} div.mathics {font-size:larger;font-weight:bold} span.mathics-zbl {float:right} div.matverw {font-size:smaller} div.review {margin:5mm 5mm 5mm 5mm} div.aunot {font-weight:bold} div.published {font-weight:bold} .number {font-style: italic; text-align:right} div.reviewer{font-style:italic;text-align:right} EN 49J52 90C30 weak sharp minima; lower- math1 functions; proximal normals; contingent cone; Mordukhovich normal cone serial article Rahmo, El Desouky Number: 6109986 Characterizations of weak sharp minima for lower- math2 functions. 2013 Summary: We derive characterizations of weak sharp minimizers of order one for the class of lower- math3 functions. The characterizations of such minimizers are obtained for a nonlinear programming problem with an abstract set constraint. The first characterization is formulated in terms of the proximal normals to a given set relative to the abstract set constraint and the directional derivative of the objective function. Two examples are given to illustrate this characterization. The other characterizations are extensions of the main characterizations of weak sharp minima for convex functions, recently proved by Burke and Deng [J. V. Burke and S. Deng, Control Cybern. 31, No. 3, 439–469 (2002; Zbl 1105.90356)], to the class of lower- math4 functions.

Number: 1254.05134 On the independence number of the strong product of cycle-powers. 2013 Summary: We determine the independence number of the strong product of cycle-powers math1 and math2 , where math3 denotes the graph obtained from the math4 -cycle math5 by adding all chords joining vertices at most math6 steps apart on the cycle. The result generalizes a similar result for odd cycles obtained by R. S. Hales [J. Comb. Theory, Ser. B 15, 146–155 (1973; Zbl 0247.05122)]. The solution is based on the problem of arranging math7 1s and math8 0s in a circle (where math9 ) in such a way that every string of math10 consecutive bits has at most math11 equal to 1. A nontrivial lower bound for the Shannon capacity of cycle-powers is obtained on the basis of the independence numbers computed. The result can also be interpreted in terms of packing rectangles into a torus. The maximum number of math12 -by- math13 rectangles that can be packed into a two-dimensional math14 -by- math15 (rectangular) torus is obtained. The proof of the main theorem can be used to determine the maximum packing itself (or the corresponding largest independent set in the product graph).
